{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_lagarde_ver02/data/sn92073203/00332893026/1937123001/0012.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE FOUR\nThe Skyland Post\nPUBLISHED EVERY THURSDAY\nED M. ANDERSON,\u2019 Editor\nOne Year in Ashe County 11.00\nOne Year Out of Ashe County-,-\u2014\u2014\u2014>l.2s\nTwo voices are there: one is of the sea,\nOne of the mountains; each a mighty voice.\n\u2014WORDSWORTH.\nHere shall the press the people\u2019s right maintain,\nUnawed by influence and unbribed by gain;\nHere patriot truth her glorious precepts draw,\nPledged to religion, liberty, and law.\n\u2014JOSEPH STORY.\nEntered as second-class matter on Oct. 1, 1925 at\nthe post office at West Jefferson, North Carolina\nNEW YEAR RESOLUTIONS\nAs the twilight of the old year begins to fade\nrapidly and as we stand on the threshold of the\nnew year, we pause to take stock -to make an\ninventory of our successes and failures during\n1937 and to re-adjust our sights, to set up new\ngoals of accomplishments for 1938.\nWe who live in this wonderful Blue Ridge\nsection of North Carolina have a lot for which\nto be thankful. Os course we had our ups and\ndowns during the past year, but fortunately we\nhave not felt any serious effects of the national\nbusiness recession. On a whole 1937 was one of\nthe most successful yaers in the history of Ashe\nand surrounding counties. Our livestock and\nagricultural products brought good prices; we\nwere not visited by any serious disasters; con\nstruction on the Parkway highway has been vir\ntually completed; crime records have been com\nparatively low; splendid improvements were\nnoted here and there. But, on the other hand,\npractically every one did certain things which\nwere not right and which have been regretted.\nThe old year is about gone and now let\u2019s turn\nour attention to the new one. What shall we do\nabout it? As personal or individual resolutions\nwe offer the following: strive to make your\nfamily and friends happier; resolve to be better\nneighbors, better citizens; make and save all of\nthe money you can, but do it honestly; plan to\nown a home or farm of your own, if you do not\nalready have one; resolve to give your child\nren the best possible educations; contribute\nmore generously in time and money to support\nof the churches; take more interest in govern\nment and give your support to its improve\nment; whatever you do, resolve to do the best\njob possible.\nFor the general welfare, civic, economic and\nindustrial welfare of the county and the Jeffer\nsons, we recommend the following: secure a\nhospital for Ashe, county, establish at least one\nindustrial plant thereby provide more opportu\nnities for employment and give additional in\ncome; seek more tourist trade by beautifying\nour homes, yards, highways, streets offering\nmore attractions and facilities and putting on a\nlarge-scale program of advertising this section\nto the rest of the world; obtain a resort estabe\nlishment on Nigger mountain; purchase a fire\ntruck for the protection of our homes and pro\nperty from the devastating ravages fire; reduce\ncrime and highway accidents; practice extensi\nvely the trade-at-home policy; work together in\nharmony and peace; organize a merchants asso\nciation and civic club in West Jefferson; secure\nmore hard surfaced highways; promote dairy\ning in this section, and have an Ashe County\nFair.\nWith our natural resources, our marvels of\nscenic beauty; the new Parkway and numerous\nother assets, this county and section have a gol\nden opportunity lying just ahead. By pulling\ntogether and working together and advertising\nwe can climb to greater heights of joy, happi\nness and prosperity.\nTo 1938 we extend a hearty welcome. We are\nlooking forward to your arrival with eager anti\ncipations. And to our readers we wish a most\nHappy and Prosperous New Year.\nTHE BIG QUESTION TODAY\nFor the first time since its birth in March,\n1933, the entire program of the New Deal ad\nministration is now facing a severe crisis and\naccording to present indications the showdown\nmay come in the regular session of Congress\nwhich convenes on January 3, rather than dur\ning the next presidential election of 1940, as had\nbeen anticipated prior to the recent business\nrecession and the special session of Congress.\nAfter four long years of one of the worst de\npressions ever experienced in America, with\nthe national income having slumped from over\neighty billion to approximately thirty-four bil\nlion, with agricultural products selling for less\nthan the cost of production, with manufactur\ners being unable to make a profit or to find a\nmarket for their goods, with unemployment\nreaching a staggering high peak, with banks.\nand business failing rapidly all over the coun\ntry, with fear and breadlines existing in every\ncommunity, the nation as a whole was face to\nface with an economic crisis.\nThose were serious days and it looked as\nthough our great capitalistic system and our\nstill greater system of democratic government\nwere falling by virtue of this economic crisis\ncaused by lack of adequate distribution.\nSomething had to be done and done at once.\nSo the courageous new president, Franklin D.\nRoosevelt, launched upon an entirely new pro\ngram of federal government activity, in an ef\nfort to reduce unemployment, raise the income\nof farmers and industrial workers, as well as\nmanufacturers, insure the safety of banks and\nnumerous other things which were completely\nforeign to our capitalistic-democratic systems.\nThe program of the New Deal was purely so\ncialistic, yet it endeavored to stay within the\nbounds of constitutional limitations.\nThe immediate effects were altogether grati\nfying and it accomplished amazing results from\na temporary or emergency standpoint. It pro\nvided the necessary amount of high-powered\nstimulation needed by the sick patient, but as a\npermanent policy, many of its features have\nbeen questionable. In fact several of them were\nkilled by the Supreme Court and it was obvious\nthat the government couldn\u2019t long continue to\nspend far more than it was collecting.\nHowever, in practically every election that\nhas been held during the past five years, includ\ning the presidential election of 1936, the New\nDeal has won by overwhelming odds. But in\n1937 the sailing of the Roosevelt ship hasn\u2019t\nbeen so smooth. The President\u2019s Supreme\nCourt plan, launched last February, hit a rough\nand rugged sea, the lawless action of dictator\nship and strife assumed by labor and labor\nleaders have muddied the waters, the big break\nin the stock market and the resulting business\nrecession and industrial inactivity have stirred\nup high waves of opposition and in response to\nall this, conservative congressmen and senators\nheeded the warnings of \u201cstop, look and listen\u201d\nand during the special session they didn\u2019t get\nfar with the administration\u2019s wage and hour\nbill, agricultural program, tax revision, govern\nmental re-organization, etc. And in the closing\nhours Senators Bailey and Vandenberg at\ntempted to form a coalition movement, de\nsigned to return to our age-old principles of\n\u201csane and safe\u201d legislation, and put an end to\ngovernmental interference with business,\ngrowth of bureaucracy and the concentration\nof powers in the hands of the president. The\nmovement was prefaced by an address to the\nAmerican public, containing an outline of ten\nbasic principles.\nShall we return to our old system and\nabandon the socialistic New Deal? That\nis the question before Congress today.\nWe don\u2019t claim to be authorities or to\nBe able to answer that question for Con\ngress, but we do not believe it would be wise to\nreturn completely to the old system, as much as\nwe like and admire it. Governmental control\nof crop production and industrial working con\nditions are absolutely essential to maintain\nbuying power and avoid collapse in the capi\ntalistic system.\nOn the other hand before setting up any\ncrop control, wage and hour legislative restric\ntions,. Congress should realize the fact that to\nday the United States no longer holds her\nunique position of having products that the rest\nof the world want and are willing to pay for.\nFor the past twenty-five years we have had a\nworkers\u2019 paradise in this country. Due the in\nventive genius of many American brains and\nto our capital, we pioneered in the fields of\ntransportation, radio, mass production of silks,\nwoolens and cottons and rayon materials, food\nitems and numerous other things that the rest\nof the world didn\u2019t have and was willing to buy\nand pay for.\nBut due to our philanthropic disposition, we\nhave taught other nations, how to make all of\nthese things in their own countries, and the re\nsult is that today we are having to compete on\nforeign markets with all other nations. There\nfore, what is the outcome?\nIt is simply this. We don\u2019t have much of a\nchance and at the same time maintain our high\nstandards of living. How can we compete when\nwe pay three times as much for labor as does\nthe next highest country in the world and\ntwelve times as much as the lowest? How can\nwe compete and still pay perhaps five times as\nmuch for the raw products as they do in other\nnations?\nThis condition is unfortunate, but neverthe\nless it is true. And the question which congress\nwill now have to decide is not so much con\ncerned with systems and principles of govern\nment, as it is with this question. Shall we at\ntempt to compete on foreign markets or shall\nwe build a high tariff wall around the United\nI States and endeavor to maintain our own high\nstandard of living without being pulled down\nby the low living standards of the rest of the\nworld?\nThat\u2019s the big question which will have to be\ndetermined before any agricultural or wage and\nhour bill can be set up on a permanent basis.\nTHE SKYLAND POST, WEST JEFFERSON, N. C.\n-O\u2014\nr UHjjtupe\nA IK, Jr\nJk\nM llWvv MwiMMWIM\nwi'hwv\u00dfK\n11\nKeteieJU\nBy\nTROY\nISAIAH\nJONES\n\u25a0tel,, -Vjtjil\nI hung up a pair of stockings\nChristmas Eve and left a note for\nSanta Claus to leave me a \u201cwoman\u201d\nin them, but he \u201cmithed\u201d me.\n\nThere came, a sleet storm in\nScotland and broke down all the\nwires. The reason was the wire\nwould not give.\n\nThere was said to be snow ten\nfeet deep in Scotland, but that did\nnot bother them for the Scotch are\nused to being in tight places.\n\nSenator Bailey is accusing the\ngovernment of \u201cShooting the Eco\nnomic Bull\u201d. As chief competitor\nhe is showing his tender spot.\n\nSomebody called the last session\nof Congress the \u201cGoose-Egg\u201d ses\nsion. They got rid of the lame\nduck session, but there is always\nsome wise crackers that is hatch\ning up something new.\n\nIf all the apron strings were laid\nend to end they would not reach\nfrom the kitchen sink to the bridge\ntable.\n\nIt is no odds for these fellows\nthat have to pet their wives by\ncalling them their little \u201cLamp\nkins\u201d. They shoud have never\npulled the wool over their eyes to\nbegin with.\n\nThis aint no new year. It is the\nold one in disguise.\n\nYou will hape to give the women\ncredit for tawing man\u2019s part. Eve\nbegan by taking a rib which is a\nspare part.\n\nA rose by any other name would\nsmell just the same. And a party\nby any other name would also\nsmell.\n\nIf Roosevelt keeps on loosing his\nteeth won\u2019t be anything left\nto go into the law.\n\nIt is all right to whip the Devil\naround the stump if you don\u2019t let\nhim overtake you.\nBRIDGE PARTY GIVEN\nHERE LAST WEDNESDAY\nMrs. Ruth Roland and Mr. and\nMrs. John Donnelly were charming\nhostesses at bridge party at the Ro\nland home on last Tuesday night.\nThe card tables were placed in\nthe living room and dining room\nwhjich were thrown en suite for\nthe occasion. The decorations were\nin keeping with the yuletide season,\nand a Christmas tree was placed\nin one corner of the living room s\nFive progressions of bridge were\nplayed and at the conclusion of the\ngame, the high score winners were\nMrs. Clifford Ray, ladies\u2019 high\nscore; Mr. Dean McMillian, gentle\nman\u2019s high and Miss Elizabeth Div\ners, floating prize.\nThe hostesses served punch and\ncake and the card tables were tak\nen out and the guest danced until\nmidnight.\nLetters To Editor\nChristmas 1937\nDear Friend:\u2014\nMay I take this means of extend\ning to you and yours Heartiest\nChristmas Greetings. I hope that\nthe New Year will be a Happy one\nfor you.\nFaithfully yours,\nJAMES A. FARLEY.\nMEADOW VIEW NEWS\nMr. and Mrs. Earl Ball snent Sat\nurday night at Mrs. Ida Tucker\u2019s\nhome.\nMr. Frank B. Sirecns and family;\nspent Xmas with his mother, Mrs.\nSmith.\nMr. Wayne Tucker visited his\nsister, Mrs. Goss Price, Thursday\nand Friday at Anowalt, W. Va. 1\nMr. Ellis Thompson and Vance, of\nKennett Square, Pa., are visiting\nhome folks.\nMr. and Mrs. Doyal Tucker spent\nSunday night at Mrs. Earl Ball.\nMiss Ruby Shepherd, of Roanoke,\nVa., i\u00a7 visiting her mother, Mrs.\nRena Shepherd.\nGrady Eastridge, of Marion, spent\nXmas holidays with Miss Flossie\nShepherd.\nDEATHS\nMRS. MARGARETTE PHIPPS\nFuneral. services for Mrs. Mar\ngarette Phipps, 40, who died at her\nhome in Grassy Creek community\nMonday, were held at the Pleasant\nValley Church Tuesday afternoon,\nwith Revs. W. E. Denney, C. G.\nBurkett and W. F. Barker conduct\ning the service.\nThe deceased is survived by her\nhusband, Chas. W. Phipps and sev\neral children \u2014Chalmer 1 Arline,\nOphelia, Bradley, Clifford and Co\nrine. She also leaves 7 brothers\nand 2 sisters, as well as her moth\ner, Mrs. Cora Cox.\nMRS. CYNTHIA PENNINGTON\nA large crowd attended the final\nrites Tuesday held for Mrs. Cyn\nthia Pennington, age 70, of Nath\nan\u2019s Creek, who died at her home\nfrom a cancer. Services were con\nducted at the Center Primitive\nBaptist church by Rev. Thompson,\nof Bel Air, Md., Elders Edd Davis,\nBlevins and Worth Davis. Inter\nment followed in the church ceme\ntery.\nMrs. Pennington is survived by\ntwo sons, Ed and Tom, both of\nwhom live in Nathan\u2019s Creek com\nmunity. Her husband died about\ntwo years ago.\nSparta News\nMiss Marjorie Holsey has been\nright sick for a few days with\npneumonia.\nMr. and Mrs. Dwight Greene\nhave an apartment in the home of\nMrs. T. J. Carson for the winter.\nMr. Alex Reeves, who has been\nconfined to his home for a while,\nis improving.\nMrs. L. C. Boyer of Charlotte\ncame up Saturday for her mother\nMrs. T. J. Carson who will spend\nsometime with her and the remain\nder of the winter in Elizabeth City\nand Washington, D. C. with her\nsons.\nMiss Ila Holman of N. Wilkesboro\nrecently donated about thirty books\nto Sparta Public Library which are\ngreatly appreciated.\nMiss Fay Joines, a student at Mars\nHill College is at home fr the holi-\ni. K.\nTHURSDAY, DECEMBER 30, 1937\ndays.\nMiss Madalyer Wagoner, who is\ntaking a beauty culture course at\nN. Wilkesboro is spnding a few\ndays at home.\nMr. and Mrs. Clemel Richardson\nand daughter, Doris, are spending\na few weeks in Florida.\nMrs. James Sturgills, Piney\nCreek, returned home laist week\nfrom Elkin hospital where she had\nbeen a patient for sometime.\nYOUR HOROSCOPE\nDECEMBER 26, 27 You have a\nhappy faculty of looking on the\nbright side of life no matter how\ndark and discouraging the present\noutlook of things may be. You\nhave the love of your children as\nyou are affectionate and kind in\nyour home. You are a great ob\nserver of conditions and things.\nJust and kindly in your decisions.\nDECEMBER 28, 29 You are a\nvery forceful, cmooth, convincing\nspeaker. While you are not secre\ntive. you do not parade your af\nfairs before the public. Every\nthing you do being in the open as\nyou have nothing to cover up. You\nare fearless, courageous and cap\nable, and do not fear to have peo\nple know what you think and do.\nDECEMBER 30, 31 The people\nwho work in your office and home\nseldom go on a strike as you are\nvery considerate of their rights and\nconcede them. You are friendly to\nall and have many friends. You\nare quick to see good in a person\nand speak a good word for them\nwhenever the opportunity presents\nitself. You are close in money\nmatters, calculating and shrewd at\na bargain, thoughtful and contemp\nlating.\nfamily and are willing to make\nfamiy and are willing to make\nwhatever sacrifice necessary to\nmake things easy and smooth for\nthem. You have many close friends\nin spite of your tendency to ans\nwere very curtly. Possessing a good\ndeal of executive ability, you like\nto take the lead in every undertak\ning, great or small.\nNOTICE A\nNORTH CAROLINA,\nASHE COUNTY.\nHaving qualified as Administra\ntrix of the estate of Sarah E.\nBrooks, deceased, late of: Ashe\nCounty, North Carolina, this is to\nnotify all persons having claims\nagainst the estate of the said Sarah\nE. Brooks, deceased, to exhibit them\nto the undersigned, at Wagoner,\nNorth Carolina, on or before the\n28th day of December, 1938, or this\nnotice will be pleaded in bar of\ntheir recovery.\nAll persons indebted to said estate\nwill please make immediate pay\nment.\nJOHNSIE BROOKS ATWOOD,\nAdministrator of Sarah E.\nBrooks, Dec\u2019d. 12-30-6tp\nNOTICE\nNORTH CAROLINA,\nASHE COUNTY.\nHaving qualified as Executors of\nthe last Will and Testament of John\nL. Wilson, deceased, late of Ashe\nCounty, North Carolina, this is to\nnotify all persons having claims\nagainst said estate to present them\nto the undersigned for payment on\nor before December 28, 1938, or this\nnotice will be pleaded in bar of their\nrecovery.\nAll persons indebted to said es\ntat a will please make prompt pay\nment to the undersigned.\nThis December 21, 1937.\nC. C. and ADDIE SUTHERLAND,\nExecutors of John L. Wilson,\ndeceased 12-30-61","height":"27261","width":"18549"}}
